*   [Benjamin Franklin College](/Benjamin_Franklin_College_(Yale_University)) – Named in tribute to [Benjamin Franklin](/Benjamin_Franklin), a prominent [Founding Father](/Founding_Fathers_of_the_United_States).

*   [Berkeley College](/Berkeley_College_(Yale)) – Honors [George Berkeley](/George_Berkeley) (1685–1753), an early and influential benefactor of Yale.

*   [Branford College](/Branford_College) – Named after [Branford, Connecticut](/Branford,_Connecticut), the town where Yale was originally founded.

*   [Davenport College](/Davenport_College) – Named for [John Davenport](/John_Davenport_(clergyman)), the founder of the city of New Haven. It is often colloquially referred to as "D'port."

*   [Ezra Stiles College](/Ezra_Stiles_College) – Named in honor of [Ezra Stiles](/Ezra_Stiles), a former president of Yale. The college's design is attributed to the renowned architect [Eero Saarinen](/Eero_Saarinen).

*   [Jonathan Edwards College](/Jonathan_Edwards_College) – Named for the influential theologian and co-founder of [Princeton University](/Princeton_University), [Jonathan Edwards](/Jonathan_Edwards_(theology)). It is commonly known as "J.E."

*   [Grace Hopper College](/Grace_Hopper_College) – Named in honor of Admiral [Grace Murray Hopper](/Grace_Murray_Hopper), a distinguished Yale Ph.D. and a pioneer in computer science. This college was formerly named for [John C. Calhoun](/John_C._Calhoun), a former Vice President of the United States, until 2017.

*   [Morse College](/Morse_College) – Named for [Samuel Morse](/Samuel_Morse), the inventor of [Morse Code](/Morse_Code). Like Ezra Stiles College, it was also designed by [Eero Saarinen](/Eero_Saarinen).

*   [Pauli Murray College](/Pauli_Murray_College) – Named in honor of [Pauli Murray](/Pauli_Murray), a trailblazing figure in civil rights activism, legal scholarship, and religious thought.

*   [Pierson College](/Pierson_College) – Named for [Abraham Pierson](/Abraham_Pierson), who served as Yale's first rector.

*   [Saybrook College](/Saybrook_College) – Named after [Old Saybrook, Connecticut](/Old_Saybrook,_Connecticut), a location where Yale was temporarily situated in its early history.

*   [Silliman College](/Silliman_College) – Named in honor of the distinguished scientist and Yale professor [Benjamin Silliman](/Benjamin_Silliman). Notably, approximately half of its structures were originally part of the [Sheffield Scientific School](/Sheffield_Scientific_School).

*   [Timothy Dwight College](/Timothy_Dwight_College) – Named in recognition of the two Yale presidents who bore the name [Timothy Dwight IV](/Timothy_Dwight_IV) and [Timothy Dwight V](/Timothy_Dwight_V). It is commonly referred to as "T.D."

*   [Trumbull College](/Trumbull_College) – Named for [Jonathan Trumbull](/Jonathan_Trumbull), who served as the governor of Connecticut during the 18th century.

### Student Organizations

#### Singing Groups

Yale College has earned a reputation as "the epicenter of college singing," a distinction stemming from its extensive history of vocal ensembles and its pivotal role in the establishment of [collegiate a cappella](/Collegiate_a_cappella) in the United States. The earliest documented choral group, the Beethoven Society, dates back to 1812. Emerging from this tradition in the mid-19th century was the [Yale Glee Club](/Yale_Glee_Club). [28] While glee clubs across the nation had fostered smaller collegiate ensembles since that period, the [Whiffenpoofs](/Whiffenpoofs), an all-senior, all-male group formed in 1909, is widely recognized as the oldest collegiate a cappella society in the United States. [29] [30] This group, formalizing a singing style that had roots in Black [barbershop groups](/Barbershop_music) in New Haven, paved the way for the formation of similar ensembles nationwide. [29] The advent of coeducation in 1969 opened the door for the establishment of all-women's groups and mixed-gender ensembles. Presently, Yale College hosts at least eighteen undergraduate a cappella groups, encompassing a diverse range from Slavic choruses to Christian a cappella ensembles. [31]

#### Publications

The tradition of student publications at Yale extends back to 1806. However, the [Yale Literary Magazine], founded in 1836, remains the oldest publication still in print and is believed to be the oldest surviving literary review in the United States. [32] [33] Following its lead, undergraduate publications such as the Yale Banner, a yearbook, and [The Yale Record], a humor magazine, emerged around the same time similar publications were being established at rival institutions like Harvard and Princeton. [34] The [Yale Daily News], established in 1878, arrived slightly later but quickly became the preeminent daily campus newspaper, continuing its publication every weekday during the undergraduate academic term. The 20th century saw the debut of numerous other publications, including [The Yale Herald] and [The New Journal].

#### Secret Societies

In 1832, a significant schism arose within the college's two primary debating societies, [Linonia] and [Brothers in Unity], concerning the induction of members into [Phi Beta Kappa]. This disagreement led a group of seniors to establish the university's first [secret society](/Secret_society), known as [Skull and Bones]. [35] This society pioneered the practice of "tapping" select juniors for membership during their senior year, a ritual that was subsequently adopted by nearly all other undergraduate senior societies. Since that time, senior societies have proliferated at Yale, with current estimates suggesting the existence of 41 such societies, and senior class membership in these organizations ranging from ten to fifty percent of each graduating class. [36] [37] [38] While once shrouded in strict secrecy, the "secret" nature of these societies has become considerably more transparent; their existence is widely acknowledged, and membership rosters for most are published annually. Ten contemporary societies—[Skull and Bones], [Scroll and Key], [Book and Snake], [Wolf's Head], [Elihu], [Berzelius], [St. Elmo], [Manuscript], [Shabtai], and [Mace and Chain]—possess their own dedicated buildings located near the campus. Many other societies utilize fixed meeting spaces on campus where they convene twice weekly. [37] Some of the oldest society buildings are characterized by their enclosed, windowless designs, leading members to refer to them as "tombs."

The activities within these societies have varied considerably over time and differ among the organizations themselves. However, common practices often include communal dinners, structured discussions, shared consumption of alcoholic beverages, and the in-depth recounting of members' life histories. [36] [39] Despite a historical legacy of social exclusion, particularly targeting Jewish individuals and women, many of these societies have, in recent decades, placed a greater emphasis on cultivating membership diversity. [40] [41] [42] The semi-secretive nature and the influential membership of Yale's established senior societies have consistently attracted considerable public interest and scrutiny. This attention has been particularly pronounced in instances where both major candidates in a [2004 U.S. presidential election] were revealed to be members of Skull and Bones. [37] [39] [43]

### In Popular Culture

*   The novel [Aunt Phillis's Cabin](/Aunt_Phillis's_Cabin), written by [Mary Henderson Eastman] as a counter-narrative to [Uncle Tom's Cabin](/Uncle_Tom's_Cabin), is partially set within the environs of Yale College during the 1850s. [44]

*   In the popular American television series [Gilmore Girls](/Gilmore_Girls), the character [Rory Gilmore](/Rory_Gilmore) pursues her higher education at Yale College, ultimately choosing it over [Harvard University](/Harvard_University).

